## Documentation structure template

Follow this structure when creating new documentation pages. Adjust as needed based on content type.

### Heading levels and the right-hand TOC

Use heading levels so the **in-page table of contents** (Docusaurus right rail) shows a **hierarchy**, not a single flat list of `##` entries.

**`##` (H2) — Major sections**

Reserve `##` for the structural blocks that frame the page. Use these headings (omit any section that does not apply):

- **`## What will you learn?`** (optional)
- **`## Prerequisites`**
- **`## Troubleshooting`**
- **`## Next steps`**

**`###` (H3) and deeper — Body content between those anchors**

Use `###` (and `####` when needed) for procedural chunks, comparisons, grouped steps, and conceptual subsections **between** Prerequisites and Troubleshooting. Prefer **at least** `###` for those stages so the TOC **indents** under the major outline instead of listing many same-level `##` siblings.

This is not a rigid rule for every page, but it should be the default when it keeps the outline intuitive.

**Exceptions**

- **Short, linear get started guides** may use `## Step 1`, `## Step 2`, … when the whole page is a tight sequence and there are few other `##` sections. If the guide grows, switch to `###` under a parent `##` or collapse steps under clearer `###` groupings.
- **Deep nesting:** Use `####` for substeps inside a `###` group when it stays readable (see Step groups under Step-by-step instructions).

**Introduction**

Keep the opening **introduction as normal paragraphs** (no `## Introduction` heading) unless a doc type requires otherwise. The first `##` in the file is often **What will you learn?** or **Prerequisites**.

### Standard structure

#### 1. Frontmatter

```yaml
---
title: Clear, descriptive title
# Optional: left navigation label (Title Case). Omit when it should match `title`.
sidebar_label: Title Case Label For Sidebar
description: One-sentence summary of what this guide covers
keywords:
  - keyword1
  - keyword2
  - keyword3
tags:
  - tag1
  - tag2
  - tag3
---
```

- **`title`:** Official page title (browser, SEO, and default sidebar label). May use phrasing that fits the page better than the nav.
- **`sidebar_label`:** Use when the **sidebar** label must differ from `title`. Sidebar labels use **Title Case** (capitalize major words). If omitted, Docusaurus derives the sidebar entry from `title`.

#### 2. Introduction (1 short paragraph, 2-3 lines)

A single concise paragraph that states what the user will accomplish and why it matters. Do not include "What will you learn?" content here—that goes in a separate section if needed.

**Visual separation:** Add a horizontal rule (`---`) before each major `##` section heading to provide clear visual separation between sections.

**Example:**
```markdown
This guide shows you how to create and configure your first IaCM workspace. Workspaces connect your Terraform configurations to infrastructure providers and manage state across your deployments.
```

Optionally include a brief list of key outcomes or topics covered in this guide. In the authored page, use an **`##`** heading so it matches the major-section pattern in [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc):

```markdown
---

## What will you learn?

- **Topic 1:** Brief description of what they'll learn.
- **Topic 2:** Another key outcome or skill.
- **Topic 3:** Additional learning objective.
```

#### 3. Prerequisites

List required setup, permissions, or knowledge. **For each prerequisite**, tell the reader how to satisfy it; don't assume they already have it.

- **"Module or feature enabled" (e.g. IaCM enabled):** State **where it appears in the UI** when available (e.g. **Infrastructure** > **Infrastructure as Code Management**). For **account access** (sign-up, SaaS vs self-managed, invitations), link to [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide)—do **not** ask readers to identify their deployment model up front. Put **if the module does not appear** guidance in a `:::info Contact Harness support:` admonition **indented with four spaces** under that prerequisite bullet so it nests in the list; inside the admonition, link the module get-started page (e.g. [Get started with IaCM](/docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started)), then account administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io). Add **self-hosted enablement** or **what’s supported** links only when the doc’s audience is clearly administrators or advanced users, not first-time onboarding.
- **Permissions (e.g. "permission to create and run pipelines"):** Name the **specific permissions** (e.g. View, Create/Edit, Execute for Pipelines), link to the [Permissions reference](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference) (use the relevant anchor, e.g. `#pipelines`), and say **how to get them** (e.g. an administrator must assign a role that includes them) with a link to [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) and/or [Manage roles](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/add-manage-roles).
- **Other items:** Link to how/where if a new user might not have it.

```markdown
---

## Prerequisites

- **Harness account with IaCM enabled:** You need **Infrastructure as Code Management** under **Infrastructure** in Harness when it is entitled on your account. For how to access or create a Harness account, see [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide).

    :::info Contact Harness support:

    If IaCM does not appear, see [Get started with IaCM](/docs/infra-as-code-management/get-started) or contact your account administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io).

    :::

- **Pipeline permissions:** You need **View**, **Create/Edit**, and **Execute** for [Pipelines](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/permissions-reference#pipelines). To get these, an administrator must assign you a role that includes them. See [RBAC in Harness](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/rbac-in-harness) and [Manage roles](/docs/platform/role-based-access-control/add-manage-roles).
- **Item 3**
```

For modules other than IaCM, keep the same pattern: **UI location** when entitled, [Getting started with Harness Platform](/docs/platform/get-started/onboarding-guide) for account access, then a `:::info Contact Harness support:` admonition (indented under that bullet with four spaces so it nests in the prerequisite list) with module **get started** plus administrator or [Harness Support](mailto:support@harness.io) if the module does not appear.

#### 4. Step-by-step instructions

Use clear sections with **imperative** headers in **sentence case** (e.g. `### Create an inventory`, not gerunds like "Creating an inventory"). Default to **`###`** for procedural blocks so they sit **between** the `##` landmarks (Prerequisites, Troubleshooting, Next steps) and produce a nested TOC, per [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc). Capitalize **proper nouns**: product and technology names (e.g. **Kubernetes**, **Terraform**, **OpenTofu**, **Harness**, **IaCM**, **AWS**) and official **Harness** UI feature names when they are branded or module names.

- **Get started guides — `## Step 1`, `## Step 2`, or `### Step 1`, `### Step 2`:** For **onboarding / get started** pages, you may use numbered step headings to emphasize a short, linear path. Prefer **`### Step N`** when other `##` sections exist on the page; reserve **`## Step N`** for very short guides per the exception in [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc). Use numbered step headings **only** for actionable procedure. Do **not** use step headings for **Prerequisites**, **Troubleshooting**, or **Next steps** (keep those as `## Prerequisites`, `## Troubleshooting`, `## Next steps`). Do not label introductory or conceptual blocks as steps.
- **Step groups:** When several steps form a logical group (e.g. module details), add a **heading for that group** (e.g. `### Module details`) and nest the steps under it (e.g. `#### Step 1`, `#### Step 2`). Add a **one-line summary** under the group heading so the reader knows what those steps accomplish (e.g. "The following steps (1–3) configure the module name, provider, connector, and storage type.").
- **Intro before lists:** **Always add a short intro sentence before every numbered or bullet list** that states what the list is for or what the reader is about to do. Do not jump straight into "1. Select...". This helps readers and LLMs understand context (e.g. "On the Execution pipeline step of the wizard, do the following:" then "1. Select a pipeline...").
- **UI elements:** For **exact** labels as they appear in the product (buttons, menu commands, setting names, strategy options), use **single quotes** (`'Mark as Failed'`) per [writing-style — Buttons and exact UI labels](mdc:writing-style.mdc). **Bold** other clickable or selectable references in steps (tabs, generic field labels) when you are not quoting the literal string; keep the same convention for each type of element throughout the page.
- **Unfamiliar actions:** When the doc tells the user to do something they might not know how to do (e.g. "run manual sync", "create the pipeline manually"):
  - If it's explained **elsewhere in the same doc**, link to that section (e.g. "For how to run the manual sync, see [Step 6: Create and run the initial sync](#step-6-create-and-run-the-initial-sync).").
  - If it's **"create X manually"**, give the UI path (e.g. "Go to **Infrastructure** > **Pipelines** > **Create a Pipeline** in your project") and link to the doc that describes it (e.g. "see [Harness Pipelines](/docs/category/pipelines)").

```markdown
---

### Create an inventory

Instructions here.

:::tip
Add troubleshooting hints inline when they help anticipate common issues.
:::

### Register a playbook

More instructions.
```

**When to include inline troubleshooting:**

- Common errors that happen during this specific step
- Configuration gotchas that prevent progress
- Quick fixes that keep the user moving forward

**Screenshots and images:**

Always add descriptive captions to provide context. Use centered alignment only for narrow screenshots (mobile UI, dialogs, small widgets).

Import the DocImage component at the top of the file (after frontmatter):

```mdx
import DocImage from '@site/src/components/DocImage';
```

**For full-width screenshots (desktop UI, dashboards, most product screenshots):**

```jsx
<DocImage path={require('./static/screenshot.png')} alt="Descriptive alt text explaining what the image shows" title="Click to view full size" />
<p align="center"><em>Clear caption that explains what users should look for in the screenshot</em></p>
```

**For narrow screenshots (mobile UI, small dialogs, less than ~75% page width):**

```jsx
<div align="center">
  <DocImage path={require('./static/mobile-screenshot.png')} alt="Descriptive alt text" title="Click to view full size" width="40%" />
  <p align="center"><em>Caption explaining the narrow screenshot</em></p>
</div>
```

**Best practices:**
- Use `path={require('./static/image.png')}` syntax for local images
- Add descriptive `alt` text for accessibility and SEO
- Set `title="Click to view full size"` to indicate the click-to-zoom functionality
- Write captions that explain the context or highlight key elements in the screenshot
- **Always center captions** using `<p align="center"><em>...</em></p>` - captions should appear centered at the bottom of the screenshot for visual consistency
- Only center screenshots that are genuinely narrow (mobile UI, small dialogs) - full-width screenshots look odd when centered
- For narrow screenshots, specify `width` prop (e.g., `width="40%"`) to control size
- Place screenshots immediately after the step or paragraph that references them

#### 5. Troubleshooting section (optional)

Only include if there are general issues not tied to specific steps.

The section title must be **`## Troubleshooting`** so it aligns with the other `##` landmarks in [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc).

Use the `<Troubleshoot>` component from `AdaptiveAIContent` — do **not** use static `### heading` + `**Solution:**` pairs **for each issue** (the `issue` prop is the per-entry heading). The component renders a collapsible entry sourced from live docs (Kapa) or pre-generated AI responses (Gemini), with a static fallback.

Import at the top of the file (after frontmatter):

```mdx
import { Troubleshoot } from '@site/src/components/AdaptiveAIContent';
```

Then in the body:

```markdown
---

## Troubleshooting
```

```jsx
<Troubleshoot
  issue="[Concise description of the problem, including product/module context for Kapa]"
  mode="docs"
  fallback="[One-sentence static fix shown if AI is unavailable]"
/>
```

**Choosing `mode`:**

- `mode="docs"` — Harness-specific issues (error codes, pipeline behaviour, module config). Kapa answers at runtime from live docs. Use for most entries.
- `mode="general"` — Infrastructure-adjacent issues (auth, networking, Terraform, Kubernetes). Gemini pre-generates a response at build time.
- `mode="fallback-only"` — Deterministic fixes where the answer never changes. Always shows the `fallback`; no AI call is made.

**Rules:**

- Do **not** add `###` headings above each component — the `issue` prop serves as the collapsible heading.
- The `fallback` prop is required on every entry.
- Write `issue` with enough context for Kapa to match the right docs (include product name, module, or error message text).
- Multiple entries sit directly adjacent with no headings between them.

**Example:**

```jsx
<Troubleshoot
  issue="Error acquiring the state lock in Harness IaCM pipeline with remote backend"
  mode="docs"
  fallback="Ensure no other process is holding a lock. Lock retries are handled automatically by OpenTofu/Terraform."
/>

<Troubleshoot
  issue="Concurrent operations conflict on the same Terraform state file with remote backend"
  mode="general"
  fallback="Each backend handles locking independently — DynamoDB for S3, object metadata for GCS, leases for Azure Blob."
/>
```

#### 6. Next steps

Wrap up with:

- **Brief conclusion** (1-2 sentences): Summarize what was accomplished
- **2-3 related links**: Most logical next actions or related docs

Use **`## Next steps`** as the heading so it stays a top-level TOC entry alongside Prerequisites and Troubleshooting.

```markdown
---

## Next steps

You've successfully [accomplished X]. You can now [key capability unlocked].

- [Related doc 1]
- [Related doc 2]
- [Related doc 3]
```

### Information architecture: DynamicMarkdownSelector (DMS) and tabs

This section is advisory when choosing layout; it does not replace the standard section order above.
The same criteria apply in Claude commands: `.claude/commands/doc-section-audit.md` (Step 5d).

#### Choosing between DMS, synced tabs, and unsynced tabs

Before choosing a component, scan sibling pages for a **structural pattern**:

1. Extract all `##` and `###` headings from each sibling page.
2. Normalize them (lowercase, drop leading articles, strip punctuation).
3. Group near-matches across pages — headings are "similar" if they share the same first 3 words
   or describe the same action with minor rewording (e.g. "Create a connector" ≈ "Add a connector").
4. Count how many sibling pages contain each heading group.

If **3+ heading groups each appear in 3+ sibling pages**, the pages share a structural pattern —
strong signal for **synced tabs**.

**Get started guide pattern** — a common variant: provider- or format-specific siblings that each
follow the same onboarding sequence (e.g. "Create a connector", "Create your workspace",
"Add a provision pipeline") but with different commands or screenshots. The headings may not be
exact matches — look for semantic equivalence. These are synced tabs candidates.

**Decision guide:**

| Signal | Best fit |
|---|---|
| 2–5 pages, short (≤150 lines each), same concept with provider/format/environment variants, 3+ shared heading groups | **Synced tabs** |
| 3+ pages, medium–long (100+ lines each), distinct self-contained topics, few shared headings | **DMS** |
| 2–5 pages, short–medium (≤100 lines each), related but independent concepts, not provider variants | **Unsynced tabs** |
| Single long page (800+ lines) that can be broken into self-contained subtopics | **DMS parent + children** |
| Most siblings manage or configure sub-features of one parent concept | **DMS with "Manage [X]" parent** |

Note: "Manage [X]" is a valid grouping label even when [X] matches the folder name — the
grouping describes management intent, not navigation duplication.

#### DynamicMarkdownSelector (DMS)

- Use when **multiple full-content child pages** exist under a shared parent concept and a **hub** page improves discoverability.
- The UI uses **grid tiles** — not limited to four or five options.
- Use DMS only when each child is a **genuine, self-contained guide**. Do **not** use DMS for short parallel sections.
- **Reference pattern:** repo file `docs/artifact-registry/get-started/quickstart.md` (parent pulls children via DMS).

**Implementation (DMS):**

- Import: `import DynamicMarkdownSelector from '@site/src/components/DynamicMarkdownSelector/DynamicMarkdownSelector';`
- Child Markdown files live under `docs/<module>/<section>/content/` and are referenced with site-style paths in `options`.
- Pass **`toc`** from MDX and bracket the component with **`precedingHeadingID`** / **`nextHeadingID`**.
- Child files may import `RedirectIfStandalone` — always pass both `label` and `targetPage` props.
  A bare `<RedirectIfStandalone />` with no props crashes at runtime.
- Child files must **not** contain `## Troubleshooting` or `## Next steps` — these belong on the parent only.
- Image paths in child files use `../static/image.png` (not `./static/`) because child files sit one
  level deeper than the parent's static folder.

#### Synced tabs

- Use when the **same concept or procedure** applies across environments, platforms, or providers and the reader needs **only one** variant at a time.
- Content differs primarily in commands, values, or screenshots — not in concepts.
- Synced tabs keep the tab choice aligned across pages sharing the same `groupId`.
- Reference: [Docusaurus synced tabs](https://docusaurus.io/docs/markdown-features/tabs#syncing-tab-choices).

#### Unsynced tabs

- Use for **2–5 shorter** parallel sections on **one** page to reduce vertical scroll.
- If sections are **long** or there are **more than ~5** options, prefer **DMS** instead.

If none of these apply, a conventional single page or sidebar navigation is fine.

### Markdown headings and sidebar

- **No `#` (h1) in the file body.** Do not use a single-hash heading in Markdown. Start the document body at `##`. The page still has an official title via frontmatter `title` (and Docusaurus may render it per theme).
- **H2 vs H3:** Follow [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc): use `##` for What will you learn?, Prerequisites, Troubleshooting, and Next steps; use `###` and deeper for instructional body content between those anchors so the right-hand TOC is hierarchical.
- **Sentence case for in-doc headings (`##`, `###`, …):** Capitalize the **first word** only, except for **proper nouns**: technologies (e.g. **Docker**, **Kubernetes**, **GitHub**), **Harness** modules and products (e.g. **IaCM**, **STO**, **CD** when referring to the module), and other trademarked or official names. Examples: `### Create a pipeline`, `### Configure the IaCM plugin`, `### Install a Kubernetes delegate` (when those are procedural sections); `## Prerequisites` for major sections.
- **Sidebar labels (navigation):** Use **Title Case** — capitalize major words in the left nav. Set this with **`sidebar_label`** when it needs to read differently from `title`, or shape the **`title`** itself in Title Case if it doubles as the sidebar label and matches the nav wording you want.

### Content guidelines

- **Headers:** Imperative, sentence case; no gerunds in step titles (prefer `### Configure the connector` over `### Configuring the connector`). Exception: concept sections may use noun phrases (`## Troubleshooting`, `## Prerequisites`). **Get started** guides may use `## Step 1` / `### Step 1`, … per [Heading levels and the right-hand TOC](#heading-levels-and-the-right-hand-toc)—only for actionable onboarding steps, not for Prerequisites, Troubleshooting, or Next steps. Gerunds are fine for broad concepts like "Understanding CI/CD" when that fits the content.
- **Lists:** When each item has a concept/action and an explanation, use **Bold label:** description. For simple self-explanatory lists, plain formatting is fine. Always add a short intro sentence before a list that states what the list is for.
- **No em dashes:** Never use em dashes (`—`) in documentation. Use commas, periods, semicolons, or rewrite sentences. In bullet points with links, use a colon after the link: `- [Link text](/path): Description here.`
- Keep prerequisites minimal and relevant; link to "how" for each.
- Include code examples where helpful.
- Use callouts (`:::tip`, `:::warning`, `:::info`) strategically.
- Link to related concepts inline, not just at the end.
